200316-as-latin-america-takes-steps-to-counter-coronavirus-brazil-s-bolsonaro-snubs-warnings|title=Latin America takes steps to counter coronavirus, Brazil's Bolsonaro snubs warnings|date=2020-03-16|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; border-right:none;\" |{{flagdeco|Yemen}}|| style=\"text-align:left; border-left:none;\" | Yemen || 5,852,325 || 267,498\n|\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Yemen]]||<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; border-right:none;\" |{{flagdeco|Zambia}}|| style=\"text-align:left; border-left:none;\" | Zambia || 3,955,937 || 56,680\n|\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zambia]]||<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''TOTAL'''||'''831,021,742'''||'''128,207,915'''\n|\n| ||<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|- \n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\" class=\"sortbottom\" |{{As of|2020|03|17}} \u2014 {{navbar|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/School closures|plain=y}}\n\n; Notes\n: a{{Note|NoteA}} Bolivia, Cayman Islands, Equatorial Guinea, Venezuela: data on enrolment in tertiary education programmes is not available.\n: b{{Note|NoteB}} China: schools have started opening, but the majority remain closed.\n: c{{Note|NoteC}} Honduras: While all schools are open, universities have the choice to remain open or not.\n: d{{Note|NoteD}} Japan: Universities currently on school spring break, and hence closures not related to the coronavirus.\n: e{{Note|NoteE}} Republic of Korea: Universities have postponed the beginning of the academic year by two weeks to 16 March.\n: f{{Note|NoteF}} Romania: Most universities remain open.\n|}\n\n=== Localised school closures ===\n10 countries have localised schools closures, UNESCO estimates  473,933,356 &nbsp;learners are potentially at risk (pre-primary to upper-secondary education) and 77,938,904 learners are potentially at risk in tertiary education.<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Country'''\n|'''Region/s'''\n|'''See also'''\n|'''Ref'''\n|-\n|[[Australia]]\n|Australia has not closed schools or universities in line with advice from the [[Australian Health Protection Principal Committee]]. Some private and independent schools have chosen to close.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karp|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/why-australia-is-not-shutting-schools-to-help-control-the-spread-of-coronavirus|title=Why Australia is not shutting schools to help control the spread of coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 22\u201323 March, the state governments of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and the [[Australian Capital Territory]] contradicted federal government advice by enacting school closures, while the [[New South Wales]] state government encouraged students to stay home from school if possible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6691357/confusion-over-coronavirus-school-closures/|title=Confusion over coronavirus school closures|first=Daniel|last=McCulloch|date=Mar 23, 2020|website=The Canberra Times|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref> Many universities closed temporarily and transitioned to [[Online learning in higher education|online learning]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/online-mass-exodus-how-australian-unis-are-coping-with-covid-19-539630|title=Online mass exodus: How Australian unis are coping with COVID-19|website=iTnews|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Bhutan]]\n|Districts of Thimphu, Paro and Punakha\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n|[[Brazil]]\n|As of 16 March, Brazil has more confirmed cases of coronavirus than any other Latin American country, however President [[Jair Bolsonaro]] has issued few country-wide measures to slow the spread of the virus.<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> Because the president and federal government failed to act regarding the pandemic and had, as of 18 March, not decided to cancel classes in the whole country, lower instances of government acted autonomously. State schools, municipal schools, private institutions and universities acted differently regarding suspending classes at once, gradually or not at all, and between replacing classes with [[distance education]] or simply postponing them. Because of that, there are only \"localised\" (as opposed to \"national\") school closures, as of 20 March, according to UNESCO.<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n\nStates such as S\u00e3o Paulo, Rio de Janeiro and Pernambuco have cancelled classes in state schools, but some municipal schools continue having classes normally even in those states.<ref name=\"g1rj13\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/rj/rio-de-janeiro/blog/edimilson-avila/noticia/2020/03/13/municipio-do-rio-vai-suspender-aulas-na-rede-publica-semana-que-vem.ghtml|title=Escolas p\u00fablicas e particulares do RJ n\u00e3o ter\u00e3o aulas a partir de segunda-feira|first=Edimilson|last=\u00c1vila|date=2020-03-13|publisher=G1 Rio de Janeiro|language=pt}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"g1sp17\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/sp/sao-paulo/noticia/2020/03/17/coronavirus-escolas-estaduais-tem-menos-de-5percent-de-presenca-e-municipais-30percent-nesta-terca.ghtml|title=Coronav\u00edrus: escolas estaduais de SP t\u00eam menos de 5% de presen\u00e7a e municipais, 30% nesta ter\u00e7a|date=2020-03-17|publisher=G1 S\u00e3o Paulo|language=pt}}</ref><ref name=\"g1pb17\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/pb/paraiba/noticia/2020/03/17/governo-da-pb-suspende-aulas-na-rede-estadual-e-recomenda-cancelamento-de-eventos-por-90-dias.ghtml|title=Governo da PB suspende aulas na rede estadual e recomenda cancelamento de eventos por 90 dias|date=2020-03-17|publisher=G1 Pernambuco|language=pt}}</ref> [[Minas Gerais]] state initially cancelled classes for public schools between for only three days<ref name=\"em15\">{{cite web|url=https://www.em.com.br/app/noticia/gerais/2020/03/15/interna_gerais,1129119/coronavirus-governo-de-minas-suspende-aulas-na-rede-estadual.shtml|title=Coronav\u00edrus: governo de Minas suspende aulas na rede estadual|first=Gabriel|last=Ronan|date=2020-03-15|publisher=Estado de Minas Gerais|language=pt}}</ref> and on 18 March, the state governor announced that classes in the region of the state capital [[Belo Horizonte]] were cancelled indefinitely, because there was confirmed [[community transmission]] in the region, but the rest of the state would continue having classes normally until further notice.<ref name=\"am18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agenciaminas.mg.gov.br/noticia/rede-estadual-tem-calendario-de-aulas-alterado-como-medida-preventiva-contra-o-coronavirus|title=Rede estadual tem calend\u00e1rio de aulas alterado como medida preventiva contra o coronav\u00edrus|date=2020-03-18|publisher=Ag\u00eancia Minas|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nIn S\u00e3o Paulo, classes are being cancelled gradually, so that parents had time to come up with solutions that didn't involve letting the kids be with their grandparents. Between 16 and 20 March, students could go to class, but absentees would not be penalised. Classes were indefinitely cancelled starting on March 23.<ref name=\"g1sp17\" />\n\nRegarding the food safety of students, some municipal and state schools announced \"food kits\" for weekly pickup such as in [[Recife]]<ref name=\"jc15\">{{cite web|url=https://jc.ne10.uol.com.br/pernambuco/2020/03/5602310-universidades-de-pernambuco-confirmam-suspensao-de-aulas-a-partir-de-segunda--16.html|title=Universidades de Pernambuco confirmam suspens\u00e3o de aulas a partir de segunda (16)|author1=Diogo Menezes Katarina Moraes|author2=Diogo Menezes Katarina Moraes|date=2020-03-15|publisher=Jornal do Commercio|language=pt}}</ref> or that some selected schools would remain open for students to have lunch, such as in [[Esp\u00edrito Santo]].<ref name=\"g1es16\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/es/espirito-santo/noticia/2020/03/16/aulas-da-rede-estadual-no-es-sao-suspensas-para-evitar-contagio-por-novo-coronavirus.ghtml|title=Coronav\u00edrus: Governo do ES suspende aulas e antecipa f\u00e9rias|date=2020-03-16|publisher=G1 Esp\u00edrito Santo|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nIn Higher Education, [[Unicamp]] was the first university of the country to cancel all classes, stating on 13 March. Initially, classes were cancelled until 31 March, but later the university extended the suspension until 12 April.<ref name=\"unicamp16\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/noticias/2020/03/16/coronavirus-resolucao-gr-242020-suspende-atividades-ate-12-de-abril|title=Coronav\u00edrus: Novo Comunicado. Reitor destaca regras para funcionamento da Universidade|date=2020-03-16|publisher=Unicamp|language=pt}}</ref> On 11 March, one student of [[University of S\u00e3o Paulo|USP]] was confirmed with the disease, leading one department to cancel classes for a single day,<ref name=\"carta11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/saude/usp-confirma-primeiro-caso-de-coronavirus-e-cancela-aulas-em-departamento|title=USP confirma primeiro caso de coronav\u00edrus e cancela aulas em departamento|first=Giovanna|last=Galvani|date=2020-03-11|publisher=Carta Capital|language=pt}}</ref> and it wasn't until 17 March that the whole university cancelled classes.<ref name=\"uol13\">{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/saude/ultimas-noticias/redacao/2020/03/13/usp-e-unesp-vao-suspender-as-aulas-a-partir-do-dia-17-de-marco.htm|title=Coronav\u00edrus: USP e Unesp suspender\u00e3o as aulas a partir do dia 17 de mar\u00e7o|date=2020-03-13|publisher=UOL|language=pt}}</ref> Many universities across the country cancelled classes, such as [[Universidade Federal de Vi\u00e7osa|UFV]] (since 16 March)<ref name=\"ufv14\">{{cite web|url=https://www2.dti.ufv.br/noticias/scripts/exibeNoticiaMulti.php?codNot=32257|title=UFV decide suspender atividades acad\u00eamicas por tempo indeterminado|date=2020-03-14|publisher=Universidade Federal de Vi\u00e7osa|language=pt}}</ref> and [[UNILA]] (since 17 March),<ref name=\"unila16\">{{cite web|url=https://portal.unila.edu.br/noticias/coronavirus-unila-suspende-aulas-e-implementa-expediente-administrativo-especial|title=Coronav\u00edrus: UNILA suspende aulas e implementa expediente administrativo especial|date=2020-03-16|publisher=Universidade Federal da Integra\u00e7\u00e3o Latino-Americana|language=pt}}</ref> but others remain open.\n\nIn the city of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is home to half of [[History of the Jews in Brazil|Brazil's 120,000 Jews]], Jewish schools have closed and some are providing class remotely over video. In Rio de Janeiro, Jewish day schools also closed in the absence of a state-wide decision regarding the closure of Rio's public and private schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/brazilian-jewish-schools-close-to-prevent-coronavirus-infections/|title=Brazilian Jewish schools close to prevent coronavirus infections|last=Gilban|first=Marcus M.|website=timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brazil]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n|[[Canada]]\n|On 16 March 2020, Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau urged Canadians to stay home and closed its borders to all foreign nationals except for US citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/justin-trudeau-closes-canada-borders-coronavirus|title='Stay home': Justin Trudeau closes Canada's borders over coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> As of 16 March at the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|provincial and territorial level]], all schools are closed due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]], with the exception of British Columbia and Yukon. However, Yukon schools began their spring break 16 March and on March 18, 2020 the closure was extended until April 15, 2020 <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-march-16-1.5498752|title=What you need to know about COVID-19 in B.C. on March 16, 2020|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|publisher=CBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/localcovid19/?region=north|title=North Coronavirus Local Updates|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|publisher=CBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/yukon-hanley-covid-update-mar-18-1.5501711|title=YYukon declares public health emergency over COVID-19 pandemic|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=CBC}}</ref> The [[University of British Columbia]], [[Simon Fraser University]], and the [[Emily Carr College of Art]] transitioned to online classes on March 16,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/news/1372416/metro-vancouvers-ubc-sfu-bcit-respond-provinces-covid-19-health-recommendations|title=Updated: UBC and SFU move to online classes as postsecondaries respond to COVID-19 recommendations|date=2020-03-13|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> and on March 17, K-12 schools in British Columbia were suspended indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6689354/john-horgan-cabinet-ministers-announce-measures-slow-spread-coronavirus/|title=B.C. suspends K-12 classes indefinitely amid coronavirus pandemic|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n|[[India]]\n|On 16 March, India declared a countrywide lock-down of schools and colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/mumbai-s-siddhivinayak-temple-to-close-entry-for-devotees-from-today-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-2195660|title=Schools Closed, Travel To Be Avoided, Says Centre On Coronavirus: 10 Points|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] asked universities to postpone exams till March 31. The board exams conducted by [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]] and [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education|ICSE]] boards have also been postponed until March 31.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/health/coronavirus-latest-updates-coronavirus-live-news-coronavirus-in-india-covid-19-symptoms-vaccine-cure-covid-19-india-delhi-maharashtra-kerala/1902845/|title=Coronavirus: PM Modi calls for 'janata curfew' on March 22, says social distancing key to fight menace|date=19 March 2020|work=The Financial Express|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n|[[Philippines]]\n|Metropolitan Manila, Manila City, Central Luzon, IIocos Region, Bulacan Province, Cavite Province, Rizal Province, Capas, and Tarlac\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n|[[Sweden]]\n|Schools have remained open.<ref name=\":15\" /> On 17 March, the government of Sweden declared that high schools, vocational schools and Universities shall remain closed and recommended continuing lectures by distance education.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7431064|title=Elever fr\u00e5n gymnasiet och upp\u00e5t ska inte vara i skolan|work=Sveriges Radio|accessdate=17 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden]]\n|\n|-\n|[[United States]]\n|As of 21 March 2020, over 118,000 public schools in the United States had closed, affecting nearly 54 million students. 46 states and Washington D.C. have implemented statewide school closures.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/section/multimedia/map-coronavirus-and-school-closures.html|title=Map: Coronavirus and School Closures|journal=Education Week|date=6 March 2020|publisher=Editorial Projects in Education|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 13 March, Virginia has instated the longest period of school closures, extending until the start of the 2020\u201321 school year.\nUS President Donald Trump announced his intention to waive all federal student loan interest, however little further information has been shared providing details on the plan.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/03/13/coronavirus-updates-us-testing-death-toll-stocks-school-closures/5032550002/|title=Coronavirus updates: Trump declares national emergency; schools in 12 states shut down; cruise lines halted|last=Stanglin|first=Grace Hauck and Doug|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe government of [[Guam]] shut down for 14 days, including all schools, starting on March 16,<ref>[https://www.pncguam.com/govguam-shut-down-for-14-days-including-all-public-and-catholic-schools/ GovGuam shut down for 14 days, including all public and Catholic school] By Mai Habib, PNC Guam, 16 March 2020</ref> one day after reporting its first three cases of COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.pncguam.com/guam-records-its-first-case-of-covid-19/ Guam records its first 3 cases of COVID-19] By Jolene Toves PNC Guam, 15 March 2020</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n|<ref>{{cite journal |title=Map: Coronavirus and School Closures |url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/section/multimedia/map-coronavirus-and-school-closures.html |journal=Education Week |date=6 March 2020 |publisher=Editorial Projects in Education |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Uruguay]]\n|As of 14 March, Uruguay will only close schools in case of registered cases of coronavirus among students.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nThe [[University of the Republic]] cancelled classes on March 13, 2020, and the government announced a two-week suspension of classes at public and private schools on Saturday, March 14. Schools were to remain open to provide meals to students, but without classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elpais.com.uy/informacion/politica/gobierno-suspende-clases-pais-semanas-coronavirus.html|title=Gobierno suspende clases en todo el pa\u00eds durante dos semanas por coronavirus|work=Diario EL PAIS Uruguay|accessdate=19 March 2020|language=spanish}}</ref>\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uruguay]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|-\n|[[Vietnam]]\n|All pre-primary, primary and lower secondary schools in Vietnam; and all upper-secondary institutions in the city of Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City, Da Nang and Hai Phong, as well as provinces of Kon Tum, Lai Chau, Lao Cai, Quang Nam, Quang Ninh, Son La, Thua Thien Hue, Tien Giang and Yen Bai.\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vietnam]]\n|<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n|}\n''Note: Figures correspond to total number of learners enrolled at pre-primary, primary, lower-secondary, and upper-secondary levels of education [ISCED levels 0 to 3], as well as at tertiary education levels [ISCED levels 5 to 8] who could be affected should localised closures become countrywide. Enrolment figures based on latest UNESCO Institute of Statistics data.''\n\n== Consequences of school closures ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nSchool closures in response to the COVID-19 pandemic have shed a light on numerous issues affecting access to education, as well as broader [[Social issue|socio-economic issues]].<ref name=\"UNESCO\" /> As of March 12, more than 370 million [[child]]ren and [[youth]] are not attending [[school]] because of temporary or indefinite country wide school closures mandated by [[government]]s in an attempt to slow the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"UNESCO\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/03/1058791|title=Coronavirus update: 290 million students now stuck at home|date=5 March 2020|website=UN News|language=en|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-school-closures-have-left-kids-feeling-scared-confused-2020-3|title=Parents are struggling to cope as coronavirus worries shut down schools, leaving kids scared and confused|last=Goldberg|first=Eleanor| name-list-format = vanc |website=Business Insider|date=8 March 2020|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> As of 29 March, nearly 90% of the world's learners were impacted by closures.<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n\nEven when school closures are temporary, it carries high social and economic costs. The disruptions they cause affect people across [[Community|communities]], but their impact is more severe for disadvantaged children and their families including interrupted learning, compromised nutrition, childcare problems and consequent economic cost to families who cannot work.<ref name=\"UNESCO\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegram.com/news/world/coronavirus-deprives-nearly-300-million-students-of-their-schooling-unesco-419714/|title=Coronavirus deprives nearly 300 million students of their schooling: UNESCO {{!}} The Telegram|last=Inc|first=Reuters| name-list-format = vanc |website=thetelegram.com|language=en|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Working parents are more likely to miss work when schools close in order to take care of their children, incurring wage loss in many instances and negatively impacting productivity.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\" /> Localised school closures place burdens on schools as parents and officials redirect children to schools that are open.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\" />\n\n=== Unintended strain on health-care system ===\nWomen often represent a large share of health-care workers and often cannot attend work because of childcare obligations that result from school closures. This means that many medical professionals are not at the facilities where they are most needed during a health crisis.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\" />\n\n=== Distance learning ===\nLack of access to technology or fast, reliable internet access can prevent students in rural areas and from disadvantaged families. Lack of access to technology or good internet connectivity is an obstacle to continued learning, especially for students from disadvantaged families.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\" /> In response to school closures caused by COVID-19, [[UNESCO]] recommends the use of [[distance learning]] programmes and [[Open educational resources|open educational applications]] and platforms that schools and teachers can use to reach learners remotely and limit the disruption of [[education]].<ref name=\"290million\">{{cite web|url=https://en.unesco.org/news/290-million-students-out-school-due-covid-19-unesco-releases-first-global-numbers-and-mobilizes|title=290 million students out of school due to COVID-19: UNESCO releases first global numbers and mobilizes response|author=UNESCO|date=4 March 2020|website=UNESCO|language=en|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTo aid in slowing the transmission of COVID-19, hundreds of libraries have temporarily closed. In the United States, numerous major cities announced public library closures, including Los Angeles, San Francisco, Seattle, and New York City, affecting 221 libraries.<ref name=\":2\" /> For students without internet at home, this increases the difficulty of keeping up with distance learning.\n\n=== Childcare ===\nSchool closures puts a strain on parents and guardians to provide childcare and manage distance learning while children are out of school.<ref name=\":3\" /> In the absence of alternative options, working parents often leave children alone when schools close and this can lead to risky behaviours, including increased influence of peer pressure and substance abuse.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\"/>\n\n=== Nutrition and food insecurity ===\n[[File:COVID-19 Free Meals Sign for Children and Students.jpg|thumb|Sign advertising a free breakfast and lunch program for children during widespread school closures due to the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States.]]\nMany children worldwide rely on free or discounted meals at schools.<ref name=\":3\" /> When schools close, nutrition is compromised.<ref name=\"UNESCO\" />\n\nNutrition plays a critical role in cognitive development and academic performance for children.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCary|first=Jennie M.|date=2006-09-01|title=Improving Access to School-Based Nutrition Services for Children with Special Health Care Needs|url=https://jandonline.org/article/S0002-8223(06)01721-4/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Dietetic Association|language=English|volume=106|issue=9|pages=1333\u20131336|doi=10.1016/j.jada.2006.07.022|pmid=16963333|issn=0002-8223}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Washington (state)|Washington State]], around 45% of the states 1.1 million students enrolled in traditional public and charter schools qualify for subsidised school meals. At least 520,000 students and their families may be affected by food insecurity as a result of school closures.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/education-lab/inslee-announces-all-washington-k-12-schools-to-close-in-an-effort-to-slow-the-spread-of-coronavirus/|title=Inslee expands coronavirus K-12 school closure, 250-person gathering ban, across Washington|last=Furfaro|first=Hannah|last2=O'Sullivan|first2=Joseph|date=2020-03-13|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-15|last3=Morton|first3=Neal|last4=Bazzaz|first4=Dahlia}}</ref>\n\n[[National School Lunch Act|School lunch programmes]] are the second-biggest anti-hunger initiative in the United States after [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program|food stamps]]. Every year, nearly 30 million children rely on schools to provide free or low-cost meals including breakfast, lunch, snacks, and even dinner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/20/818300504/schools-race-to-feed-students-amid-coronavirus-closures|title=Schools Race To Feed Students Amid Coronavirus Closures|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Alabama]], where state-wide school closures as of 18 March have affected over 720,000 students, the state Superintendent announced that staff in schools disproportionately affected by poverty would create meal distribution networks to provide food for students who rely on school lunches.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/alabama-closes-all-k-12-schools.html|title=Alabama closes all K-12 schools, first COVID-19 case confirmed in Jefferson County|last=Powell Crain|first=Trisha|date=2020-03-13|website=al|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Student learning outcomes ===\nSchool closures negatively impact student learning outcomes.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\"/> Schooling provides essential learning and when schools close, children and youth are deprived opportunities for growth and development. The disadvantages are disproportionate for under-privileged learners who tend to have fewer educational opportunities beyond school.<ref name=\"290million\" />\n\nStudent drop-out rates tend to increase as an effect of school closures due to the challenge of ensuring all students return to school once school closures ends. This is especially true of protracted closures.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\"/>\n\nSchools are hubs of social activity and human interaction. When schools are closed, many children and youth miss out of on social contact that is essential to learning and development.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\"/>\n\nWhen schools close parents are often asked to facilitate the learning of children at home and can struggle to perform this task. This is especially true for parents with limited education and resources.<ref name=\"UNESCO-consequences\"/>\n\n=== Special education services ===\nPotential impacts of school closures and reliance on distance learning are not addressed in federal acts{{Where|date=April 2020}} of legislation at this time{{When|date=April 2020}}.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ies.ed.gov/ncser/pdf/pl108-446.pdf|title=Public Law 108-446|last=|first=|date=|website=uscode.house.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n== Impact on formal education ==\n[[File:COVID-19 School closure sign in Williamsport, PA, USA.jpg|thumb|An electronic sign announces public school closures due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania|Williamsport]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States|USA]]]]{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nFormal education \u2014 as opposed to ''[[informal education]]'' or ''[[Nonformal learning|non-formal education]]'' \u2014 tends to refer to schools, colleges, universities and training institutions.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|last=Coombs, Philip H. (Philip Hall), 1915-2006.|title=Attacking rural poverty; how nonformal education can help|date=1974|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|others=Ahmed, Manzoor, 1940-, World Bank., International Council for Educational Development.|isbn=0-8018-1600-9|location=Baltimore|pages=|oclc=897554}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://infed.org/mobi/informal-non-formal-and-formal-education-a-brief-overview-of-some-different-approaches/|title=informal non-formal and formal education \u2013 a brief overview of some different approaches {{!}} infed.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> A 1974 report by the [[World Bank]] defined formal education as the following:<blockquote>''Formal education'': the hierarchically structured, chronologically graded \u2018education system\u2019, running from primary school through the university and including, in addition to general academic studies, a variety of specialised programmes and institutions for full-time technical and professional training.<ref name=\":21\" /></blockquote>The majority of data collected on the number of students and learners impacted by COVID-19 has been calculated based on the closure of formal education systems.<ref name=\"en.unesco.org\">{{cite web|url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures|title=COVID-19 Educational Disruption and Response|last=|first=|date=2020-03-04|website=UNESCO|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>  The [[UNESCO Institute for Statistics]] provides figures on students impacted by COVID-19 corresponding to the number of learners enrolled at pre-primary, primary, lower-secondary, and upper-secondary levels of education [<nowiki/>[[International Standard Classification of Education|ISCED]] levels 0 to 3], as well as at tertiary education levels [ISCED levels 5 to 8].<ref name=\"en.unesco.org\"/>\n\n=== Early childhood education ===\n{{See also|Early childhood education}}\n\n[[File:Stevens Elementary School during COVID epidemic 05.jpg|thumb|left|Playground at a Seattle elementary school is closed due to the epidemic on 25 March]]\nEarly childhood educational programmes are usually designed for children below the age of 3 and may refer to [[preschool]]s, [[Preschool|nursery schools]], [[kindergarten]]s, and some [[Child care|day care programmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.naeyc.org/about-us|title=About Us {{!}} NAEYC|website=www.naeyc.org|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> While many primary and secondary schools have closed around the world due to COVID-19, measures impacting early childhood educational programmes have varied. In some countries and territories,{{Which|date=April 2020}} preschools and day cares are considered necessary services and have not closed in tandem with broader school closure measures.{{Cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn the United States, the Washington State Department of Children, Youth, and Families encouraged child care and early learning centres to stay open. Some school districts may offer alternative child care options, prioritising the children of first responders and healthcare workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/education-lab/social-distancing-is-impossible-in-a-preschool-child-care-during-coronavirus/|title='Social distancing is impossible in a preschool': Child care during coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The governor of Maryland mandated that specific child care services remain open for the children of emergency personnel while Washington State and California have left it to the discretion of care providers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/coronavirus/bs-md-hogan-preschools-health-coronavirus-pandemic-20200321-5tl7bexdz5futgg2q3sj4b6z5q-story.html|title='I don't understand': Petition calls on Maryland Gov. Hogan to close child cares amid coronavirus pandemic|last=Oyefusi|first=Daniel|website=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://calmatters.org/health/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-california-child-care-providers-parents-kids/|title=Coronavirus has Californians asking: Who'll watch the kids?|date=2020-03-21|website=CalMatters|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> California Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] explained his state's position, saying \u201cWe need our child care facilities, our daycare centers, to operate to absorb the impact of these school closures.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Colorado has encouraged the development of \"tool kits\" for parents to use at home to emulate the lessons children would have received in their early learning programmes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://denverite.com/2020/03/13/what-denver-daycares-and-preschools-are-doing-about-coronavirus/|title=What Denver daycares and preschools are doing about coronavirus|date=2020-03-13|website=Denverite|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn Japan, Prime Minister Shinzo Abe closed all schools throughout the country until April 8, however, children's daycare facilities were excluded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/957bf9f6-594f-11ea-a528-dd0f971febbc|title=Japan shuts all schools to combat coronavirus|last=Harding|first=Robin|last2=Inagaki|first2=Kana|date=February 27, 2020|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> In early March, five adults associated with a nursing facility for preschool children in [[Kobe]] tested positive for coronavirus. After testing over one hundred children at the facility, a preschool student was found to be carrying the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020031200144/coronavirus-cluster-suspected-at-child-facility-in-kobe.html|title=Coronavirus Cluster Suspected at Child Facility in Kobe|date=2020-03-12|website=nippon.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Primary ===\nPrimary or elementary education typically consists of the first four to seven years of formal education.  \n[[File:Empty classroom 2020.jpg|thumb|An empty classroom in closed elementary school due to COVID-19 in [[Kikinda]], [[Serbia]]]]\n\n=== Secondary ===\n[[File:Winston-Salem Street School closure.jpg|thumb|A sign on a closed local school because of the coronavirus]]\nThe [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization]] (IBO) canceled the examinations for its [[IB Diploma Programme|Diploma Programme]] and [[International Baccalaureate#Career-related Programme (CP) curriculum outline|Career-related Programme]] candidates scheduled between 30 April and 22 May 2020, reportedly affecting more than 200,000 students worldwide. The IBO stated that it would award candidates their diplomas or certificates based on \"their coursework\" and \"the established assessment expertise, rigor, and quality control already built into the programme.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Jasmine |title=International Baccalaureate cancels May exams worldwide |url=https://harbourtimes.com/2020/03/23/international-baccalaureate-cancels-may-exams-worldwide/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Harbour Times |date=23 March 2020 |location=Hong Kong}}</ref>\n\n=== Tertiary (higher) ===\nTertiary education, also known as higher education, refers to the non-compulsory educational levels that follow completion of secondary school or high school. Tertiary education is normally taken to include [[undergraduate]] and [[postgraduate education]], as well as [[Vocational education|vocational education and training]].  Individuals who complete tertiary education generally receive [[Academic certificate|certificates]], [[diploma]]s, or [[academic degree]]s.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/education/information/nfsunesco/doc/isced_1997.htm|title=International Standard Classification of EducationI S C E D 1997|date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319192113/http://www.unesco.org/education/information/nfsunesco/doc/isced_1997.htm|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==== Undergraduate education ====\nUndergraduate education is education conducted after [[secondary education]] and prior to [[post-graduate education]], for which the learner is typically awarded a [[bachelor's degree]].<ref name=\":22\" />  Students enrolled in higher education programmes at [[college]]s, [[University|universities]], and [[community college]]s are often refereed to in countries such as United States as \"college students.\"{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe closure of colleges and universities has widespread implications for students, faculty, administrators, and the institutions themselves.\n\nColleges and universities across the United States have been called upon to issue refunds to students for the cost of [[Tuition payments|tuition]] and [[room and board]].<ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2020/03/21/coronavirus-college-students-online-closing-private-liberal-arts/2889546001/|title=Small colleges were already on the brink. Now, coronavirus threatens their existence|last=Jesse|first=David|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Belkin|first=Melissa Korn and Douglas|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/to-fight-coronavirus-colleges-sent-students-home-now-will-they-refund-tuition-11584625536|title=To Fight Coronavirus, Colleges Sent Students Home. Now Will They Refund Tuition?|date=2020-03-19|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n===== Impact on graduation ceremonies =====\n\n===== Impact on local economies =====\nIn the United States of America, Colleges and universities operate as \"mini-cities\" which generate significant revenue for cities, states, and regions.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-10/college-towns-to-clear-out-with-virus-upending-local-businesses|title=College Towns to Clear Out as Virus Upends Local Businesses|date=2020-03-10|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en}}</ref> For example, [[Princeton University]] contributed $1.58 billion [[United States dollar|USD]] to the [[New Jersey]] economy and students spent about $60 million in off-campus spending.<ref name=\":24\" /> College and university closures have a [[domino effect]] on economies with far-reaching implications.<ref name=\"fastcompany-economic-impacts\" />\n\nAccording to [[Linda Bilmes]] of the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]], \"local hotels, restaurants, cafes, shops, car rental agencies and other local businesses obtain a significant share of annual revenue from graduation week and college reunions... these communities will suffer a lot of economic damage if the colleges remain closed at that time.\"<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nSmall towns which rely on college students to support the local economy and provide labour to local businesses are especially impacted by school closures and the exodus of students from campus.<ref name=\":23\" /> In [[Ithaca]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Cornell University]] students spent at least $4 million a week in [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins county]]. In the wake of Cornell's decision to keep students home following spring break and transition to virtual instruction, the Mayor of Ithaca called for \"immediate and forceful federal action \u2014 we will see a horrific economic impact as a result of Cornell University closing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ithacajournal.com/story/news/local/2020/03/11/economic-impact-ithaca-cornells-closing-coronavirus/5022867002/|title=Loss of Cornell students during coronavirus pandemic could cost Ithaca, Tompkins $4M a week|last=Platsky|first=Jeff|website=Ithaca Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Recommended alternatives ==\n[[UNESCO]] is sharing 10 recommendations during this period:\n\n# '''Examine the readiness and choose the most relevant tools:''' Decide on the use high-technology and low-technology solutions based on the reliability of local power supplies, internet connectivity, and digital skills of teachers and students. This could range through integrated digital learning platforms, video lessons, MOOCs, to broadcasting through radios and TVs.\n# '''Ensure inclusion of the distance learning programmes:''' Implement measures to ensure that students including those with disabilities or from low-income backgrounds have access to distance learning programmes, if only a limited number of them have access to digital devices. Consider temporarily decentralising such devices from computer labs to families and support them with internet connectivity.\n# '''Protect data privacy and data security:''' Assess data security when uploading data or educational resources to web spaces, as well as when sharing them with other organisations or individuals. Ensure that the use of applications and platforms does not violate students\u2019 data privacy.\n# '''Prioritize solutions to address psychosocial challenges before teaching:''' Mobilize available tools to connect schools, parents, teachers, and students with each other. Create communities to ensure regular human interactions, enable social caring measures, and address possible psychosocial challenges that students may face when they are isolated.\n# '''Plan the study schedule of the distance learning programmes:''' Organise discussions with stakeholders to examine the possible duration of school closures and decide whether the distance learning programme should focus on teaching new knowledge or enhance students\u2019 knowledge of prior lessons. Plan the schedule depending on the situation of the affected zones, level of studies, needs of students needs, and availability of parents. Choose the appropriate learning methodologies based on the status of school closures and home-based quarantines. Avoid learning methodologies that require face-to-face communication.\n# '''Provide support to teachers and parents on the use of digital tools:''' Organise brief training or orientation sessions for teachers and parents as well, if monitoring and facilitation are needed. Help teachers to prepare the basic settings such as solutions to the use of internet data if they are required to provide live streaming of lessons.\n# '''Blend appropriate approaches and limit the number of applications and platforms:''' Blend tools or media that are available for most students, both for synchronous communication and lessons, and for asynchronous learning. Avoid overloading students and parents by asking them to download and test too many applications or platforms.\n# '''Develop distance learning rules and monitor students\u2019 learning process:''' Define the rules with parents and students on distance learning. Design formative questions, tests, or exercises to monitor closely students\u2019 learning process. Try to use tools to support submission of students\u2019 feedback and avoid overloading parents by requesting them to scan and send students\u2019 feedback\n# '''Define the duration of distance learning units based on students\u2019 self-regulation skills:''' Keep a coherent timing according to the level of the students\u2019 self-regulation and metacognitive abilities especially for livestreaming classes. Preferably, the unit for primary school students should not be more than 20 minutes, and no longer than 40 minutes for secondary school students. \n# '''Create communities and enhance connection:''' Create communities of teachers, parents, and school managers to address sense of loneliness or helplessness, facilitate sharing of experience and discussion on coping strategies when facing learning difficulties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.unesco.org/news/how-plan-distance-learning-solutions-during-temporary-schools-closures|title=How to plan distance learning solutions during temporary schools closures|date=2020-03-06|website=UNESCO|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Medicine|Education}}\n*[[List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on science and technology]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Free-content attribution\n| title = 290 million students out of school due to COVID-19: UNESCO releases first global numbers and mobilizes response\n| author = \n| publisher = UNESCO\n| page numbers = \n| source = \n| documentURL = https://en.unesco.org/news/290-million-students-out-school-due-covid-19-unesco-releases-first-global-numbers-and-mobilizes\n| licence statement URL = https://en.unesco.org/news/290-million-students-out-school-due-covid-19-unesco-releases-first-global-numbers-and-mobilizes\n| licence = CC BY-SA 3.0 IGO\n}}\n\n{{